    "title": "AI & Robotics Snacks — April 19, 2026",
    "date": "2026-04-19",
    "tags": ["Anthropic revenue", "Claude Opus 4.7", "AI desktop apps", "Oracle layoffs", "VC funding records", "semiconductor memflation"],
    "fresh": true,
    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** — April 19, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 💰 Anthropic Is Now a $30 Billion/Year Business. The \"Nonprofit\" Phase Was a While Ago.\n\nAnthropic's annualized revenue has reportedly surpassed $30 billion, possibly edging out OpenAI's numbers — and they dropped Claude Opus 4.7 this week with better agentic coding, sharper reasoning, and high-res image support up to 2576px.\n\n- **Revenue milestone:** From burning cash on alignment research to $30B annualized revenue in a few years. The \"safety-first AI company\" narrative is intact; the balance sheet looks more like a hyperscaler.\n- **Claude Opus 4.7:** Improved agentic workflows, scaled tool use, better reasoning. Every model release is now a quiet arms race entry.\n\n*The company founded to make AI safer is now racing OpenAI for the title of largest AI revenue. The irony is baked in.*\n\n**Sources:** [Crescendo AI](https://www.crescendo.ai/news/latest-ai-news-and-updates)\n\n---\n\n## 🖥️ Everyone Is Trying to Own Your Desktop. Google. Perplexity. All of Them.\n\nThe AI platform wars moved to the OS layer this week: Google launched a native Gemini app for Mac (Option + Space for instant access) and a Search app for Windows, while Perplexity dropped its Personal Computer app for Mac — all on the same day.\n\n- **Google's push:** Gemini for Mac includes image generation, video analysis, file understanding. Google Search for Windows launched April 18. Two new apps in one day.\n- **Perplexity's move:** Personal Computer for Mac joins the desktop AI rush. The goal isn't to be an app — it's to be the layer you reach for before opening anything else.\n\n*Five years ago, the browser was the platform. Now it's the system tray.*\n\n**Sources:** [9to5Mac](https://9to5mac.com/2026/04/15/google-launches-gemini-app-heres-what-it-offers/) | [FileHippo News](https://news.filehippo.com/2026/04/april-18-tech-news-roundup-google-releases-gemini-for-mac-and-a-search-app-for-windows-perplexitys-personal-computer-for-mac-debuts/)\n\n---\n\n## 📧 Oracle Laid Off 20,000–30,000 People via a 6 AM Email\n\nOracle sent a brief 6 AM email notifying an estimated 20,000 to 30,000 employees of their termination — the largest single tech layoff event of 2026, and a new benchmark for how not to handle a mass workforce reduction.\n\n- **The numbers:** Somewhere between 20k and 30k — \"estimated\" because Oracle apparently didn't feel the need to be precise. The email was brief. The careers were not.\n- **The context:** Q1 2026 saw 80,000+ tech layoffs across 247 events, with 48% explicitly attributed to AI automation. Oracle's haul in one morning surpasses some companies' entire headcount.\n\n*\"AI is creating jobs\" is technically true. Oracle's 6 AM email is doing something slightly different.*\n\n**Sources:** [Tom's Hardware](https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/tech-industry-lays-off-nearly-80-000-employees-in-the-first-quarter-of-2026-almost-50-percent-of-affected-positions-cut-due-to-ai)\n\n---\n\n## 🚀 Q1 2026: VCs Put $297 Billion Into Startups. $242 Billion Went to AI.\n\nGlobal startup funding hit $297 billion in Q1 2026 — with AI taking $242 billion, or roughly 80% of all venture capital deployed worldwide. Four of the five largest VC rounds ever recorded closed in a single quarter.\n\n- **The rounds:** OpenAI $122B, Anthropic $30B, xAI $20B, Waymo $16B. These aren't rounds — they're sovereign wealth fund allocations wearing a VC badge.\n- **The math:** If AI is 80% of VC, then \"venture capital\" now mostly means \"AI funding.\" Everything else is rounding error.\n\n*Diversification is apparently a concept for other asset classes.*\n\n**Sources:** [Crunchbase News](https://news.crunchbase.com/venture/record-breaking-funding-ai-global-q1-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## 💾 Gartner: Semiconductors Will Hit $1.3 Trillion This Year. NAND Flash Is Up 234%.\n\nGartner forecasts global semiconductor revenue will exceed $1.3 trillion in 2026 — a 64% jump — driven by AI hardware demand and what analysts are now calling \"memflation\": DRAM up 125%, NAND flash up 234%.\n\n- **Memflation:** Memory chip prices inflating sharply because AI training and inference require enormous memory bandwidth. The term is doing a lot of work in earnings calls right now.\n- **The beneficiaries:** ASML raised its 2026 revenue guidance to €36–40 billion despite China export restrictions. When the whole stack is AI, chip equipment companies win regardless of which AI company is winning.\n\n*The AI gold rush doesn't need AI to be profitable. It just needs the pickaxes to sell.*\n\n**Sources:** [Gartner](https://www.gartner.com/en/newsroom/press-releases/2026-04-08-gartner-forecasts-worldwide-semiconductor-revenue-to-exceed-us-dollars-one-point-3-trillion-in-2026) | [CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/04/15/asml-q1-2026-earnings-report.html)"
  }
]
